    \section{Coursera - Capstone Project for IBM Data Science Professional
Certificate}\label{coursera---capstone-project-for-ibm-data-science-professional-certificate}

\subsubsection{\texorpdfstring{"The battle of the neighborhoods"
\textbf{by Jimson Sulit
@jmsulyt}}{"The battle of the neighborhoods" by Jimson Sulit @jmsulyt}}\label{the-battle-of-the-neighborhoods-by-jimson-sulit-jmsulyt}

\textbf{Description}

This is the capstone project for the IBM Data Science Professional
Certificate \textgreater{}
https://www.coursera.org/learn/applied-data-science-capstone/home/info

\textbf{Objective:} As a potential business owner, we would like to see
the best neighborhoods in Sydney to put up our very own Café' business.
As a major australian city, Sydney is famous for its very dynamic local
coffee scene. With this project, we will try to see where we should put
up our own Café' and see if there are other insights we can draw from
the geographical data that we will analyze.

\textbf{Data Sources:} (data sets used are hosted on the github
repository but will be elaborated below)

\begin{quote}
https://github.com/jmsulyt/Coursera\_Capstone
\end{quote}

\textbf{GitHub repository}

\begin{quote}
https://github.com/jmsulyt/Coursera\_Capstone
\end{quote}

\textbf{Project Action Steps:}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Import Needed Libraries} - Ensure all needed libraries that
  will be used are imported
\item
  \textbf{Scrape the Data} - Use BeautifulSoup to scrape the
  geographical data needed for our project
\item
  \textbf{Create List to Catch Scraped Data} - The data that we scraped
  should be placed in a holder for later use
\item
  \textbf{Preprocess Data} - Use preprocessing and cleaning techniques
  to prepare our data for analysisV
\item
  \textbf{Get Data Coordinates} - Create a function to get coordinate
  data of suburbs/neighborhood
\item
  \textbf{Merge Coordinates to Original Dataframe} - Merge coordinates
  data with the original data
\item
  \textbf{Create a map of Sydney with neighborhood data superimposed on
  top} - initial visualization for data
\item
  \textbf{Get Top 100 Venues in 2000 m radius} - See how its
  distribution can help us
\item
  \textbf{Analyze the Findings} - Check findings from the data
\item
  \textbf{Analyze each neighborhood} - Check the data on each
  neighborhood
\item
  \textbf{Cluster Neighborhoods} - Using K-Means Clustering, cluster
  data in 6 groups
\item
  \textbf{Visualize Resulting Clusters} - See different cluster in
  visualization
\item
  \textbf{Examine the six clusters} - Draw insights from the numbers
  generated by the analysis
\item
  \textbf{Part 3} - Venue clustering by neighborhood and analysis of
  'best' fit for new location
\item

{\color{incolor}In [{\color{incolor}11}]:} \PY{c+c1}{\PYZsh{} define a function to get coordinates}
         \PY{k}{def} \PY{n+nf}{get\PYZus{}latlng}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{neighborhood}\PY{p}{)}\PY{p}{:}

             \PY{c+c1}{\PYZsh{} loop until you get the coordinates}
             \PY{k}{while}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{lat\PYZus{}lng\PYZus{}coords} \PY{o+ow}{is} \PY{k+kc}{None}\PY{p}{)}\PY{p}{:}
                 \PY{n}{g} \PY{o}{=} \PY{n}{geocoder}\PY{o}{.}\PY{n}{arcgis}\PY{p}{(}\PY{l+s+s1}{\PYZsq{}}\PY{l+s+si}{\PYZob{}\PYZcb{}}\PY{l+s+s1}{, Australia}\PY{l+s+s1}{\PYZsq{}}\PY{o}{.}\PY{n}{format}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{neighborhood}\PY{p}{)}\PY{p}{)}
                 \PY{n}{lat\PYZus{}lng\PYZus{}coords} \PY{o}{=} \PY{n}{g}\PY{o}{.}\PY{n}{latlng}

\end{Verbatim}

    \textbf{Observations / Conclusions:}

Most of the Cafes seem to be concentrated in the central areas of
Cluster 2 and Cluster 4, with the highest number in Cluster 2. Cluster 0
trails behind but still shows a good number of cafe presence for
thriving competition among service providers, we could say that there is
moderate competition in this area. However, this is limited to fewer
suburbs near the central business district. Clusters 1, 3, and 5 seems
to have very low number to totally no cafes in the neighborhood. With
this, we see a representation of a great opportunity and potential to
open new cafes as there is very little to no competition from existing
cafe businesses. Meanwhile, cafes in Cluster 2 are likely suffering from
fierce competition due to oversupply and high concentration of cafes.
This could may as well apply to Cluster 4. From another perspective,
this also shows that the oversupply of cafes mostly happened in the
central business district and areas of Sydney, with those farther from
the business areas still have very few cafes. For this, the findings
from this project recommends property developers to capitalize on our
data to open new cafes in neighborhoods in Clusters 1, 3, and 5. In
terms of identifying the least amount of competition, Cluster 1 seems
like a viable area for businesses to establish their place and names.
Lastly, property developers are advised to avoid the clusters which
already have high concentration of shopping malls and suffering from
intense competition.
